<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

<style>
body {
  margin: 0;
  background: #000;
  color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);
  font-family: Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
  font-size: clamp(16px, 2.5vw, 20px);
  line-height: 1.8;
}

/* Container */
.page {
  max-width: 640px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: clamp(80px, 14vh, 140px) clamp(28px, 8vw, 72px);
}

/* Title */
.title {
  font-size: clamp(18px, 2.2vw, 24px);
  font-style: italic;
  letter-spacing: 0.12em;
  margin-bottom: 60px;
  opacity: 0.9;
}

/* Text */
.text {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 28px;
}

/* Paragraph */
.text p {
  margin: 0;
}

/* Optional: slightly faded lines */
.soft {
  opacity: 0.6;
}

/* Optional: subtle shift */
.shift {
  opacity: 0.8;
  letter-spacing: 0.02em;
}
</style>
</head>

<body>

<div class="page">

  <div class="title">
    Am I a writer?
  </div>

  <div class="text">
    
    <p>
      I used to think it had to be something official.
    </p>

    <p>
      Something you become.
    </p>

    <p class="soft">
      Something someone else confirms.
    </p>

    <p>
      I remember sitting at a table that was too big for me,  
      writing a story about a guinea pig that had more personality than I did.
    </p>

    <p>
      I didn’t look up once.
    </p>

    <p class="shift">
      The lines on the paper told my letters where to stand.  
      Nobody told me where I was supposed to.
    </p>

    <p>
      At some point, I stopped writing.
    </p>

    <p class="soft">
      Or maybe I just stopped calling it that.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now it happens again.
    </p>

    <p>
      I see something.  
      I feel something.
    </p>

    <p>
      And it has to go somewhere.
    </p>

  </div>

</div>

</body>
</html>
